{
  "text": "Hepatitis B virus (HBV), another virus encapsidating a RNA genome, which undergoes reverse transcription and shares several features of its replication cycle with FVs, seems to have another mechanism of RNA packaging. It encodes a core protein with N-terminal assembly and C-terminal nucleic acid binding domain, the latter being strongly enriched in basic amino acids (reviewed in [CITATION_1] ). In contrast to orthoretroviruses, encapsidation of HBV pregenomic RNA (pgRNA) requires HBV polymerase (P-protein) coexpression, preferentially in cis, and P-protein binding to a 5\u2032 RNA stem loop structure within the pgRNA molecule [CITATION_2] [CITATION_3] . However, in vivo the specificity of pgRNA packaging is further influenced by the phosphorylation status of the core protein, although it was demonstrated that it possesses phosphorylation-independent unspecific RNA binding activities in vitro [CITATION_4] [CITATION_5] . Whether released HBV particles also contain encapsidated cellular RNAs has not been investigated to date.",
  "correct_citation": {
    "[CITATION_1]": "28441242",
    "[CITATION_2]": "4312932",
    "[CITATION_3]": "8238382",
